AFRICAN HORSE SICKNESS - SOUTH AFRICA (MPUMALANGA)
*************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: 23 Mar 2006
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: BuaNews Online, Cape Town, South Africa, 23 Mar 2006 [edited]
<http://www.buanews.gov.za/view.php?ID=06032316151004&coll=buanew06>

State veterinarians are investigating a possible outbreak of African
Horse Sickness (AHS) in Mpumalanga. They have confirmed that 2 wild
horses at Kaapsehoop have died of AHS.
"When speaking to private vets we found that a number of cases
they've treated have also been linked to AHS," said provincial chief
director of veterinary services, Dr Paul Kloeck.
Local tour operators and foresters have reported more deaths in the
mountains around Kaapsehoop, which is home to one of South Africa's
few wild horse populations and is a popular draw card for both local
and international tourists. The horses are the descendants of horses
used during the gold mining era over a century ago.
AHS starts as a fever and then attacks the animal's lungs, eventually
causing it to suffocate to death. The horse may also develop swelling
around the eyes and eyelids, cheeks, lips tongue, neck and shoulders.
There is a vaccine, but Dr Kloeck said it would be difficult to
capture and vaccinate the wild horses. "We can only urge horse owners
to vaccinate their horses and keep them locked indoors at night," he said.
Dr Kloeck attributed the emergence of the disease to heavy rainfall
and humidity in the Lowveld, which increased the number of insects
called culicoides midges that spread the disease.
"Mpumalanga records about 10 AHS cases annually. The rains and humid
weather are suitable for culicoides midges which pass on the disease
to horses," said Dr Kloeck.
He said most cases were reported in February 2006 but that the
prolonged rains meant there could be more cases until June. "We
expect the cases to increase until June when it starts cooling down
and the midges start dying off," said Dr Kloeck.
He said although donkeys and zebras could also contract the disease,
they did not die from it. "This disease only kills horses and cannot
be transmitted to humans," said Dr Kloeck.
He urged that all suspicious cases be immediately reported to a
veterinarian as if left untreated, there was a 95 percent chance the
animal would die.
--
