<promed@promedmail.org>
[The province of Mpumalanga is in northeastern South Africa and
contains 5 game and conservation parks, including the famed Kruger
National Park. Maps and locations of countries surrounding South
Africa as well as the situation of Mpumalanga within South Africa may
be found at the following links:
<http://www.safarinow.com/destinations/Mpumalanga/map.aspx>
<http://encarta.msn.com/map_701514875/Mpumalanga.html> as well as a
relief map: <http://www.sa-venues.com/maps/mpumalanga-relief.htm>
The causative agent for African Horse Sickness (AHS) is a
viscerotropic virus, family Reoviridae, genus Orbivirus.
AHS is regarded as endemic in the central tropical regions of Africa.
However, the disease has made its way out of the region, appearing in
the Near and Middle East, Spain, and Portugal.
AHS spreads rapidly, with an incubation period as short as 2 days,
but often as long as 7- 14 days. Generally animals have a sub-acute
fever and malaise that often allow the disease to go unnoticed. The
subacute form is sometimes referred to as the cardiac form, producing
high fevers and astounding swellings of the supraorbital fossa (the
depression normally above a horse's eye protrudes dramatically) and
the eyelids, the thorax region and shoulders. The animals usually
succumb within a week.
There is also a respiratory form producing fever, dyspnea, and
coughing. The nostrils are dilated and frothy foam oozes from the
nostrils. The conjunctiva is very red. The animal is focused on
breathing and death is often attributed to anorexia.
A mixed form of these may occur, producing more mild respiratory
signs that do not appear to progress. There is still edematous
swelling and effusions. Death is usually within a week from cardiac
failure. Often the cardiac form is present and is suddenly followed
by the pulmonary form and sudden worsening of the animal's condition.
Lesions are consistent with the clinical signs, consisting of
respiratory edema of the lungs, hydropericardium, petechial
hemorrhages within the pericardium, myocarditis, gelatinous edema
within the neck and thoracic region, pleural effusion, and
hemorrhagic gastritis.
Some photos of lesions and clinical signs may be found at:
<http://www.spc.int/rahs/Manual/images/african_horse_sickness.htm>
Approximately 70-95 percent of all horses developing the disease will
die, yet the mortality percentage for mules is only about 50 percent
and only 10 percent in donkeys.
Generally it is transmitted by _Culicoides_ spp. midges and not
considered to be directly transmitted. Occasionally it appears to be
transmitted by several species of mosquitoes, including _Culex_,
_Anopheles_, _Aedes spp_ and by the ticks _Hyalomma_ and _Rhipicephalus_.
This particular virus favors warmer conditions, when it has a
preferred vector available. It may move best in moist, mild
conditions and travel long distances on the wind-borne vectors.
Infected horses remain viremic for approximately 18 days, although
the fever may be present for another 4 to 8 days, if the animal
should live that long. Despite their reduced mortality, the viremic
stage in donkeys may last for up to 28 days. Zebras appear to be very
similar to donkeys in this regard.
Differential diagnosis should include anthrax, trypanosomiasis,
piroplasmosis, purpura hemorrhagica, equine infectious anemia, and
equine viral arteritis. However, supraorbital edema is not often seen
in other diseases on the differential list. The most prevalent form
of the virus may dictate if the supraorbital edema is present.
The virus may be isolated for identification with ELISA or PCR;
however, there is no effective treatment. However, there is
prevention with several types of vaccine, from monovalent to
polyvalent. And certainly elimination of vector exposure is an aid in
control. - Mod.TG]
